Do you remember your first experience with vinyl? There’s nothing quite like it. I feel like I lived this scene from “Almost Famous” when I was 10 years old. I was bored, snooping around at my aunt’s house on a rainy day when I started looking through the old records on the shelf. I saw that there was a Bob Dylan record, I thought it was cool because we had the same name (mine is “Dillon” but close enough) when I figured out how to work the stereo, my mind was blown. I remember my blood pumping faster, it’s like I was getting the biggest dopamine hit of my 10 year old life. I was obsessed. I listened to every record on that shelf, but Bob Dylan’s “Highway 61 Revisited” was my favorite. I could never shake my obsession with records, but I wouldn’t have it any other way. They have become a huge part of my life. I’ve met so many friends, and learned so much new music. I discover dozens of records every single week. The pull only gets stronger. Now, it’s amazing that I feed my family with the proceeds of the shop, and I get to see people in every stage of collecting. What an honor it is to be part of the community.
Tell me about your first experience with records in the comment section!

I remember the first time I watched this video. It was way before YouTube. Back then, if you wanted to watch a video on the internet, you had to download it, which took probably 8-12 hours. I heard about this video as a young guitar student, and hit download on the family computer before going to bed one night. This was probably 2001 Limewire. The next day I woke up and pushed play, and my mind was blown. I called my dad in the living room to show him. He said “and thats the best guitar player ever?” 🤣 he didn’t get it, but I did. I studied his hands, how he hammered the frets and plummeted the Whammy bar into divebomb glory. How he played with the sustain, and experimented with the sacred tune of American pride. It was and is so beautiful to me.
So many amazing moments in music history were never captured on film, I am so thankful that this exists.

Led by explosive guitar player Chris (later Christa) Bond, THUNDER and ROSES was a power-trio from Philly in the best tradition of Cream or the Jimi Hendrix Experience.
 
This is their sole album, originally released in 1969. A cult psychedelic hard-rock classic, including “White Lace and Strange”, famously covered by Nirvana.
 
Thunder and Roses (named after a story from The Astounding Science Fiction Anthology) started to take form when genius 18-years old guitar player Chris Bond and bassist Tom Schaffer met heavy drummer George Emme (previously of The Electric Power House). Rehearsing six days a week the trio gelled quick and soon they were playing memorable shows at venues like Electric Factory and the Trauma.
 
Recorded at Sigma Sound by Joe Tarcia, “King of the Black Sunrise” was released by United Artists in 1969. Dominated by Bond’s outstanding fuzz-wah guitar playing, the album featured seven original songs plus a storming cover of Hendrix’s “Red House”. Sadly, the record label took a wrong decision when refused to release the killer “White Lace and Strange” as a 45 to promote the album, choosing the mockery “Country Life” instead.
 
After Thunder & Roses split, guitar player and main songwriter Chris Bond had a successful career as producer, songwriter, arranger and session musician, working closely with Daryl Hall & John Oates as well as other top artists. Later in his life, Chris eventually transitioned from male to female and changed her name to Christa. She sadly passed away in 2019.
 
*Remastered Sound
*Original artwork in hard cardboard sleeve
*Fold out insert with liner notes by Klemen Breznikar (It’s Psychedelic Baby) and photos

Wow. Today was such a remarkable day. We drove a total of 10 hours round trip, to a cabin on the side of a mountain in rural Tennessee, to buy a very carefully curated collection of 2,500 Records that have been stored away since 1992. It was a mind-blowing collection, but beyond that, the men selling the collection gave me a day I will never forget. This Father and Son were not record collectors, but 31 years ago, their Son/Brother, tragically passed away, leaving them his collection. They did not care for, or even know most of these records, but they poured over them for years trying to catch glimpses of their boy who was taken way too young. It was the most emotional experience I’ve ever had during a collection buy. These are more than records, they felt that what he would have wanted, is these records back out, being loved again after all these years. Stay tuned for a YouTube video. I’ll try to make a good one for this. It was just so special. It’ll be hard to put into words. I came home, and cried telling my wife the story. It’s so beautiful how they respected and honored these records because they were important to him. I wish they could all be this special. Stay tuned for more. 🙏
